{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9efdad52-cbaf-4328-9dcb-175a3abc5f0b","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look for **Apple's built-in crash reports**:\n\n1. **Crash logs** are saved automatically by `ReportCrash` at:\n   - `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (user apps)\n   - `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (system/services)\n\n   Files are named like `YourApp_<date>_<host>.ips` (or `.crash` on older macOS).\n\n2. **View via Console.app** → sidebar → *Crash Reports*.\n\n3. **Core dumps** (if you want a full dump for lldb):\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ./your-app        # reproduce the crash\n   ls /cores/         # core files land here\n   ```\n   Then debug with `lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> ./your-app`.\n\nThe `.ips`/`.crash` report includes the crashing thread, backtrace, and signal info — often enough to diagnose the issue without a full core dump.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a91dc749-eabc-4734-a133-57386d1e1773","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT app on macOS without `createdump`. This is a knowledge question, not a code task.","outputTokens":312,"requestId":"7841:2671F1:47D388:5333F7:69FA9D83"},"id":"de9e36da-8033-4537-ad05-140a9726c9fc","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:46:52.973Z","parentId":"0d1ddc88-80c2-4e43-93f4-30a0f89f1c39"}
